29145,"French Constitutional Court broadly approves Surveillance Act",https://euobserver.com/justice/129760,"<p>First proposed in March in the aftermath of the Charlie Hebdo shootings in Paris, the Surveillance Act allows French intelligence agencies to spy on citizens with almost complete impunity. Despite opposition from rights groups and a petition signed by over 100,000 people, MPs passed the bill into law in late June anyway.</p><p>The act empowers intelligence agencies - under the authority of the prime minister’s office - to monitor anyone. A warrant or any other type of court approval is not needed. A dedicated special advisory group made up of magistrates, MPs, and senators will instead be consulted.</p><p>The French Constitutional Court press release is available <a href=""http://www.conseil-constitutionnel.fr/conseil-constitutionnel/francais/les-decisions/acces-par-date/decisions-depuis-1959/2015/2015-713-dc/communique-de-presse.144139.html"">here</a>.</p>",2,"2015-07-27 13:03:15",FR,privacy,"france, fundamental-rights, intelligence-agencies, data-protection, warrant, cybersecurity, surveillance, privacy",government
