107228,"Entry into Force of the French Digital Republic Bill",https://www.huntonprivacyblog.com/2016/10/31/entry-force-french-digital-republic-bill/,"<p>The French Digital Republic Bill was enacted after a final vote from the Senate. The Bill aligns the French legal data protection framework with the EU General Data Protection Regulation requirements before the GDPR becomes applicable in May 2018. The Bill significantly increases the maximum level of fines for violations of the French Data Protection Act. The French Data Protection Authority will be able to immediately impose a fine of up to €3 million (previously, fines could not exceed €150,000) until the GDPR becomes applicable. The Bill also gives any consumer the right to obtain, free of charge, a copy of any of his/her data resulting from the use of a service provided by an online communication service provider, except for data that has been “significantly enriched” by the service provider. Any data subject will be able to specify their wishes regarding the retention, erasure and transfer of their personal data after death. These wishes can be recorded by a trusted digital third party certified by the CNIL. The data subject can also request that any of their personal data that was collected as a minor is erased.</p>",1,"2016-10-31 23:36:00",FR,privacy,"gdpr, france, data-protection, legislation",government
